                    <span>This a treat for science buffs, the theoies are great. If you<BR>are just a average joe, watch without sound and skip the people<BR>talking.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">5 hours and 28 minutes of pure fun.</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      /
                      <span>5</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2004-04-24</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Travel to what the future MAY be like, 5 millions years from now, 100 million years from now and 200 million years from now. It is a solid mixture of science mixed with wonder as we shoot ahead, through an Ice Age, a heat wave lasting millions of years and many other changes that force animals to change and evolve to survive. Most of it is very interesting and while the DVDs have no extras, the episodes do, in the form of scientists explaining in detail what examples of animals in the past or in the present allowed them to design such wonderful new future creatures. They also talk about social behavior, changes to the climate and to the Earth's land mass itself.<BR>Sometimes the CG looks a tad fake, but kiddies should enjoy it. Be warned, like many nature shows there are predators killing prey or animals 'failing' to survive.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Absolutely Breathtaking Glimpse Into Earth's Future</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>7</span>
                      /
                      <span>7</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2004-02-21</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>To put it simply, if you enjoyed the Walking With Dinosaurs documentaries you'll love The Future Is Wild. Luscious photography, and terrific cgi mixed with live action effects.<BR>In this future of the earth depicted here, mankind is long<BR>extinct. Earth has returned to it's primitive paradise. Strange<BR>and stranger new life forms have emerged. Such as giant landwalking squids, monolithic turtles, and carnivorous fish that literally electrifies their prey. And many strange vistas.<BR>Many of today's leading scientists were consulted for this<BR>documentary to present their views of earth's future. Extremely<BR>entertaining. If you are looking for something truly out of the ordinary, The Future Is Wild is your ticket. Enjoy.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Better than what you've seen on TV!!!</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>0</span>
                      /
                      <span>0</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2004-01-30</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Despite the fact that the narrator on this fine 3-DVD set somewhat annoyingly pronounces evolution "ee-volution," fungi "fung-GEE," algea "al-GEE," and says "future beetles" so that it sounds like "fuchsia beetles" when the beetles are obviously not fuchsia, this product is worth buying! I am even going to take screenshots from this fantastic DVD boxed set. First of all, it is NOT the same programs you've seen on Animal Planet, with that much more irritating narrator who insists on showing us the humans showering, from some unspecified corner of the universe, their satellites to future Earth and sending back photos, over and over and over again. That annoyed me because it made the show feel like some science fiction trip. IT'S NOT. This DVD makes everything clear and totally believable because it has a narrator that treats the material seriously, frequent scientist comments that explain the reasoning behind it all, and extended sequences. On TV we didn't see footage of certain animals like Spitfire Birds and we didn't learn of the Toraton mating ritual. Also included are impressive modern-day animals such as the white praying mantis that disguises as a lotus flower, & the amazing armor-plated anteater called the pangolin.<P>Watch out for Prof. Bruce Tiffney; he's a funny guy, to say the least. A quintessential "mad scientist"-looking man, I must say. The DVD's are long; one is over two hours, the others are an hour and forty minutes apiece. Thirteen episodes neatly divided showcase perfectly for viewers the well-predicted animals of the future we will never see. My personal favorites would have to be the: Gryken, Scrofa, & Desert Rattleback (Disc 1), the swampus, reef glider, & Great blue windrunner (Disc 2), and the garden worm, rainbow squid, & Desert Hopper (Disc 3). To sum it up, the DVD set is completely awesome! Colorful, informative, and fascinating. I give it two thumbs way up!</span>
                  
              
